words <- stringr::words
#(a) Words starting with "y"
w_a <- str_subset(words, "^y")
print(w_a)
[1] "year"      "yes"       "yesterday" "yet"       "you"       "young"    
#(b) Words ending with "w"
w_b <- str_subset(words, "w$")

Exercise 3

# Loading a book "Pride and Prejudice" from Jane Austen's collection
austen <- janeaustenr::austen_books()
pp <- austen %>%
  dplyr::filter(book == "Pride & Prejudice")

word_freq <- pp %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)
Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
word_freq %>%
  filter(n > 100) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word)) +
  geom_col(fill = "orange") +
  labs(title = "Most Frequent Words in 'Pride and Prejudice(Count >100)'",
       x = "Count", y = "") +
  theme_minimal()
# Word cloud
set.seed(42)
wordcloud(words = word_freq$word,
          freq = word_freq$n,
          max.words = 100,
          random.order = FALSE)

s <- map_data("state")
c <- map_data("county")

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = c, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "white", color = "skyblue") +
  geom_polygon(data = s, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = NA, color = "darkblue") +
  coord_map("albers", lat0 = 30, lat1 = 40) +
  labs(title = "United States Map with State and County Boundaries") +
  theme_minimal()
